/-
Equality
%%%
tag := "sec-equality"
%%%
-/
import Mathlib
/-
[First-order logic with equality][first-order-logic-with-eq] impose two axioms, reflexivity and substitution principle, on equality.{margin}[Substitution principle is also called Leibniz's law.] These two axioms imply its remaining [basic properties][eq-basic-properties], including symmetry and transitivity. In Lean, reflexivity is the most fundamental property, as it is an interface to definitional equality.

[first-order-logic-with-eq]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First-order_logic#Equality_and_its_axioms
[eq-basic-properties]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equality_(mathematics)#Basic_properties

The basic properties alone do not guarantee that equality is non-vacuous. When equality is considered on a fixed type, the basic properties may hold simply because all pairs of expressions of that type are equal. In Lean, equality is non-vacuous on most types.{margin}[`Prop` is a type on which equality is vacuous. This is stating the proof irrelevance.]

In fact, an inductive type can be viewed as being freely generated by its constructors in the sense of constructor distinctness and injectivity. The former states that applications of distinct constructors are not equal, while the latter states that applications of the same constructor at distinct arguments are not equal.

The proofs of constructor distinctness and injectivity use the recursor of the inductive type together with the basic properties of equality.


# Definitional equality and reflexivity
%%%
tag := "sec-definitional-equality"
%%%


We have made extensive use of {lean}`rfl`, which is simply the constructor {lean}`Eq.refl` of {lean}`Eq`, with both the arguments implicit. It proves reflexivity of equality.
-/
#print rfl

example : @rfl = @Eq.refl := rfl

example (Оұ : Sort u) (a : Оұ) : a = a := rfl
/-

The applicability of `rfl` as a proof is entirely determined by the definitional equality implemented by the kernel. To demonstrate this, we define our own versions {lean}`Eq` and {lean}`rfl`.
-/
inductive Eq' {Оұ : Sort u} (a : Оұ) : Оұ вҶ’ Prop where
  | refl : Eq' a a

def rfl' {Оұ : Sort u} {a : Оұ} := @Eq'.refl Оұ a
/-
These behave identically to {lean}`Eq` and {lean}`rfl` as far as definitional equality is concerned:

1. Proof irrelevance
-/
example
  (p : Prop) (proofвӮҒ proofвӮӮ : p) : Eq' proofвӮҒ proofвӮӮ
:= rfl'
/-

2. Function $`\eta`-equivalence
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (ОІ : Sort v) (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ) : Eq' (О» x вҶҰ f x) f
:= rfl'
/-

3. Structure $`\eta`-equivalence
-/
example
  (Оұ : Type u) (ОІ : Type v) (x : Оұ Г— ОІ)
  : Eq' вҹЁx.1, x.2вҹ©  x
:= rfl'
/-

4. $`\beta`-, $`\delta`-, and $`\zeta`-reductions
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (ОІ : Sort v) (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ) (a : Оұ)
  : Eq' ((О» x вҶҰ f x) a) (f a)
:= rfl'

def в„•_to_в„• := в„• вҶ’ в„•
example : Eq' в„•_to_в„• (в„• вҶ’ в„•) := rfl'

example : Eq' (let t := в„•; t вҶ’ t) (в„• вҶ’ в„•) := rfl'
/-

5. $`\iota`-reduction
-/
example (n : в„•) :
  Eq' (@Nat.rec (О» _ вҶҰ в„•) 0 (О» m _ вҶҰ m) (Nat.succ n)) n
:= rfl'
/-

Moreover, the kernel performs reductions of different kinds until the normal form is obtained.
-/
example (n : в„•) :
  let pred (n : в„•) := n - 1
  Eq' (pred (Nat.succ n)) n
:= rfl'
/-

Of course, `Eq'` and `rfl'` also tell apart expressions that are not definitionally equal.
```lean +error
example : Eq' 0 1 := rfl'
```


# Substitution principle

Substitution principle is formulated as follows: if `a = b` and `P a` holds for a predicate `P`, then `P b` holds. We can prove it using the recursor
-/
example :
  (Оұ : Sort u) вҶ’ (a : Оұ) /- parameters -/ вҶ’
  (motive : (x : Оұ) вҶ’ a = x вҶ’ Sort v) /- motive -/ вҶ’
  motive a (Eq.refl a) /- minor premise -/ вҶ’
  (b : Оұ) /- index -/ вҶ’
  (h1 : a = b) /- major premise -/ вҶ’
  motive b h1 /- codomain -/
:= @Eq.rec

example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ)
  (h1 : a = b) (h2 : P a)
  : P b
:= @Eq.rec
  Оұ a /- parameters -/
  (О» x _ вҶҰ P x) /- motive -/
  h2 /- minor premise -/
  b /- index -/
  h1 /- major premise -/
/-

The proof works, since the codomain `motive b h1` is `P b`,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ P x)
  P b = motive b h1 := rfl
/-
and since `h2` has the type of the minor premise,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ) (h2 : P a) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ P x)
  motive a (Eq.refl a) := h2
/-
This type is simply the proposition `P a`,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ) (h2 : P a) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ P x)
  motive a (Eq.refl a) = P a := rfl
/-

A short proof is obtained by letting Lean infer all implicit arguments.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ)
  (h1 : a = b) (h2 : P a)
  : P b
:= Eq.rec h2 h1
/-

Proofs by pattern matching are translated to a similar use of `Eq.rec` as above.{margin}[We could replace `rfl` on the left of `=>` with `Eq.refl _`. Using `rfl` avoids having to ignore the explicit parameter of `Eq.refl`.]
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ)
  (h1 : a = b) (h2 : P a)
  : P b
:=
  match h1 with
  | rfl => h2
/-

Substitution principle is available as a theorem, with the predicate as an implicit parameter called `motive`, in line with `Eq.rec`.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ)
  (h1 : a = b) (h2 : P a)
  : P b
:= Eq.subst h1 h2
/-

Named arguments allow specifying implicit parameters explicitly. {index}[`(вҖҰ := вҖҰ)`]
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (P : Оұ вҶ’ Prop) (a b : Оұ)
  (h1 : a = b) (h2 : P a)
  : P b
:= Eq.subst (motive := P) h1 h2
/-


# Basic properties of equality

Equality is an [equivalence relation][equivalence-relation], namely it is

* reflexive: `a = a` for all `a`,
* symmetric: if `a = b` then `b = a` for all `a` and `b`, and
* transitive: if `a = b` and `b = c` then `a = c` for all `a`, `b`, and `c`.

[equivalence-relation]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalence_relation

With reflexivity already established, it remains to prove symmetry and transitivity.
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) : b = a
:= Eq.subst (motive := О» x вҶҰ x = a) h rfl

example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) (h2 : b = c)
  : a = c
:= Eq.subst h2 h1
/-

In Lean, the following substitution is called _congruence_: if `a = b` and `f` is a function, then `f a = f b`.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (ОІ : Sort v) (a b : Оұ) (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ)
  (h : a = b)
  : f a = f b
:= Eq.subst (motive := О» x вҶҰ f a = f x) h rfl
/-

Symmetry, transitivity, and congruence are available as theorems.
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) : b = a
:= Eq.symm h

example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) (h2 : b = c)
  : a = c
:= Eq.trans h1 h2

example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (ОІ : Sort v) (a b : Оұ) (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ)
  (h : a = b)
  : f a = f b
:= congrArg f h
/-


# Constructor distinctness

Expressions given by distinct constructors of an inductive type are not equal. This _constructor distinctness_ can be proven using the substitution principle. As an illustration, we show that `0 = n + 1` leads to a contradiction by applying the substitution principle to the predicate
-/
def P (n : в„•) : Prop
:=
  match n with
  | 0 => True
  | m + 1 => False
/-
Indeed,
-/
example (n : в„•) (h : 0 = n + 1) : False :=
  let : P 0 := trivial
  Eq.subst h this
/-

Recall that `В¬` is syntactic sugar. Additional syntactic sugar is provided.
-/
example (n : в„•) :
  (В¬(0 = n + 1)) = (0 = n + 1 вҶ’ False)
:= rfl

example(n : в„•) : (0 вү  n + 1) = (0 = n + 1 вҶ’ False) := rfl
/-

Here is a reformulation of the above contradiction, with a proof that uses `Nat.rec` directly.
-/
example (n : в„•) : 0 вү  n + 1
:=
  О» h вҶҰ
  let P : в„• вҶ’ Prop := Nat.rec True (О» _ _ вҶҰ False)
  have : P 0 := trivial
  Eq.subst h this
/-

Here is a proof by pattern matching.
-/
example (n : в„•) : 0 вү  n + 1 := nofun
/-


# Constructor injectivity

Applications of a constructor at distinct arguments are not equal. Equivalently, _constructor injectivity_ holds: if two constructor applications are equal, then the arguments are equal as well. This can be proven using deconstruction together with congruence and transitivity.
-/
example (n m : в„•) (h : Nat.succ n = Nat.succ m) : n = m
:=
  let pred : Nat вҶ’ Nat := Nat.rec 0 (О» k _ вҶҰ k)
  have hpp : pred (Nat.succ n) = pred (Nat.succ m)
    := congrArg pred h
  have hnp : n = pred (Nat.succ n) := rfl
  have hpm : pred (Nat.succ m) = m := rfl
  Eq.trans hnp (Eq.trans hpp hpm)
/-

Lean generates an injectivity theorem for each constructor taking fields, unless those fields appear in constructor's codomain.
-/
example (n m : в„•) (h : Nat.succ n = Nat.succ m) : n = m
:= Nat.succ.inj h

inductive Nat' : Type where
  | zero : Nat'
  | succ : Nat' вҶ’ Nat'

example (n m : Nat') (h : Nat'.succ n = Nat'.succ m) : n = m
:= Nat'.succ.inj h
/-

For constructors with multiple arguments, injectivity yields equalities for each argument.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Type u) (ОІ : Type v) (pairвӮҒ pairвӮӮ : Оұ Г— ОІ)
  (h : pairвӮҒ = pairвӮӮ)
  : pairвӮҒ.fst = pairвӮӮ.fst вҲ§ pairвӮҒ.snd = pairвӮӮ.snd
:= Prod.mk.inj h
/-

No injectivity theorem is generated for `Eq.refl` since it has no fields.

```lean +error
#print Eq.refl.inj
```


# Further proofs

We will give proofs of symmetry, transitivity, and congruence directly using `Eq.rec`.


## Symmetry

-/
example :
  (Оұ : Sort u) вҶ’ (a : Оұ) /- parameters -/ вҶ’
  (motive : (x : Оұ) вҶ’ a = x вҶ’ Sort v) /- motive -/ вҶ’
  motive a (Eq.refl a) /- minor premise -/ вҶ’
  (b : Оұ) /- index -/ вҶ’
  (h : a = b) /- major premise -/ вҶ’
  motive b h /- codomain -/
:= @Eq.rec

example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) : b = a
:= @Eq.rec
  Оұ a /- parameters -/
  (О» x _ вҶҰ x = a) /- motive -/
  rfl /- minor premise -/
  b /- index -/
  h /- major premise -/
/-
The proof works, since the codomain `motive b h` is `b = a`,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ x = a)
  (b = a) = motive b h := rfl
/-
and since {lean}`rfl` has the type of the minor premise,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a : Оұ) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ x = a)
  motive a (Eq.refl a) := rfl
/-
This type is simply the proposition `a = a`,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a : Оұ) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ x = a)
  (a = a) = motive a (Eq.refl a) := rfl
/-
It admits the proof {lean}`rfl`.

A short proof is obtained by letting Lean infer all implicit arguments.
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) : b = a
:= Eq.rec rfl h
/-

Proofs by pattern matching are translated to a similar use of `Eq.rec` as above.
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h : a = b) : b = a
:=
  match h with
  | rfl => rfl
/-


## Transitivity

-/
example :
  (Оұ : Sort u) вҶ’ (b : Оұ) /- parameters -/ вҶ’
  (motive : (x : Оұ) вҶ’ b = x вҶ’ Sort v) /- motive -/ вҶ’
  motive b (Eq.refl b) /- minor premise -/ вҶ’
  (c : Оұ) /- index -/ вҶ’
  (h2 : b = c) /- major premise -/ вҶ’
  motive c h2 /- codomain -/
:= @Eq.rec

example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) (h2 : b = c)
  : a = c
:= @Eq.rec
  Оұ b /- parameters -/
  (О» x _ вҶҰ a = x) /- motive -/
  h1 /- minor premise -/
  c /- index -/
  h2 /- major premise -/
/-
The motive `О» x _ вҶҰ a = x` is different from the one in the proof of symmetry: its body is `a = x` while for symmetry it was `x = a`. The proof works, since the codomain `motive c h2` is `a = c`,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h2 : b = c) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ a = x)
  (a = c) = motive c h2 := rfl
/-
and since `h1 : a = b` has the type of the minor premise,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ a = x)
  motive b (Eq.refl b) := h1
/-
Indeed,
-/
example (Оұ : Sort u) (a b : Оұ) :
  let motive := (О» x _ вҶҰ a = x)
  (a = b) = motive b (Eq.refl b) := rfl
/-

A short proof is obtained by letting Lean infer all implicit arguments.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) (h2 : b = c)
  : a = c
:= Eq.rec h1 h2
/-

A proof by pattern matching is translated to a similar use of `Eq.rec` as above.
-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (a b c : Оұ) (h1 : a = b) (h2 : b = c)
  : a = c
:=
  match h2 with
  | rfl => h1
/-


## Congruence

-/
example
  (Оұ : Sort u) (ОІ : Sort v) (a b : Оұ) (f : Оұ вҶ’ ОІ)
  (h : a = b)
  : f a = f b
:= Eq.rec rfl h
